okay, probably we don't want to set the Mcrit when LW=0 to be
molecular cooling threshold...
So tracking literature finds that in the old times, people were using
mu = 0.59 for neutral gas as well (see Wise & Abel07). This might be
the reason why the normalization is close to TtoM(T=600, mu=0.59).
Since TtoM(T=600, mu=1.22) gives very small mass < 1e5, which ought
to have minimal contribution to photons. I'm renaming some value while
keeping the function for molecular_cooling_threshold

Fast Fcoll Tables approximation implemented

Flag FAST_FCOLL_TABLES within FlagOptions toggles whether it turns on. Significant improvement in Fcoll table calculation and no loss in precision.

Fixed sigmaM interpolations for FAST_FCOLL_TABLES

If FAST_FCOLL_TABLES is True the code requires reaching large variances to work, so it has to go down to 2e4 Msun even for larger Mturn. This can be revisited later if precision does not matter as much and we want to win more speed

Fixed Mass limits in initialiseSigmaMInterpTable

If max limit is too small it'll crash for very large radii

Deactivated the FAST_FCOLL_TABLES options for ACGs by default

ACGs are the ones that suffer the most from loss of precision at low z from the FAST_FCOLL_TABLES approximation, so we deactivate the approximation for them by default. It can be turned on with the FLAG_FAST_ATOMIC flag in Constants.h for advanced users. This does not result in a significant speed reduction for boxes with HII_DIM>=100

First commit

This branch will include the effect of the DM-baryon relative velocities onto the code. This is mainly in minihaloes (MCGs, where Mturn depends on the relative velocity vcb), but it also suppresses the matter power spectrum a bit, which affects MCGs and ACGs. This is only included at the average level since it is not a huge effect and it's very costly otherwise

Add hooks and purge IC data to conserve memory.

This adds the `hooks` keyword to each of the lower-level and higher-level functions.
This makes it possible to do essentially *anything* after computing any of the outputs,
including writing it. It also means that the user can specifically choose which boxes
to write out.

It also adds routines to prepare ICs for perturb and spin_temp, i.e. dropping all the boxes
it doesn't need, and retaining all the ones it does. Only does this if the box is written
to cache, so we know we can get the dropped data back again if required.
